classes.title: INTRO TO CINEMA
classes.description: An introduction to the study of film as an aesthetic and   social phenomeno n, and to various methods of critical   analysis.

classes.title: ROBOTS TO CYBORGS
classes.description: Born as industrial artifacts, robots, androids, and cyborgs have become rep resentations of our fears, our hopes, and our expectations of the future. T his course looks at the historical representation of human-like creations, from robots to cyborgs, and discuss media technology, techno-militarization , trans-humanism and posthumanism in the context of science-fiction cinema, literature, and new media.

classes.title: MEDIA CRITICISM
classes.description: Develop the analytical tools required for a critical   understanding of the interrelationship between media, culture,   and society in America. Special attention given to how social   structures shape media and how media products in return affect   our cultural practices and patterns.

classes.title: ADV FILM ANALYSIS
classes.description: A study of the basic formal dimensions of cinema: narration, space, time, a nd sound.

classes.title: INDEPENDENT STUDIES
classes.description: Selected research under the direction of a faculty member.

classes.title: TOPICS IN FILM PROD
classes.description: Focus on one or more aspects of film production such as   music, writing, directing, design, acting, independent filmmaking,   cinematography, producing. Topics will vary.

classes.title: TOPICS IN FILM PROD
classes.description: Focus on one or more aspects of film production such as music,   writing, directing, design, acting, independent filmmaking,   cinematography, producing. Topics will vary.

classes.title: PROFESSIONAL DEVELO
classes.description: Provides an overview of the career paths available to Film and Media Studie s students as well as a practical understanding of how various industries o perate. Also matches students with careers that meet their intellectual and professional goals.

classes.title: STAR WARS
classes.description: Class will explore the Star Wars franchise as an American phenomenon that b ecame an international powerhouse by considering it in relation to the foll owing: the origins of the blockbuster and the development of the super-bloc kbuster; George Lucas's inspiration and auteur influences; the significance of the franchise for subsequent Star Wars auteurs; and in terms of the fra nchise's enormous critical and fan responses.

classes.title: INTRO ENV MEDIA
classes.description: Ties the acquisition of critical viewing skills for film to   the practice of conceiving and writing short environmental   documentaries.  Students screen narrative films and   documentaries, deconstruct them, and use their new proficiency   to write their own documentary treatments.

classes.title: STORYTELLING SCREEN
classes.description: Part one of a two-part program. Aimed at students who already have basic sc reenwriting strengths, and are in the intermediate-to-advanced skill range. While focus will depend on the writer-in-residence, the course will includ e sessions in plot and structure, character and dialogue, tension and confl ict, tone and symbolism, and revision strategies.

classes.title: WORKSHOP FOR SCREEN
classes.description: Part two of a two-part program. Team workshop structure will allow students to expand their screenwriting skills through a fundamental and intensive s tory-writing experience, an immersive and craft-focused writing calendar, w ith access to seasoned writers. Emphasis on multiple rounds of table-readin gs and group critiques.

classes.title: CULTURAL THEORY
classes.description: This course introduces students to theoretical approaches and frameworks th at are crucial to understanding our social and cultural contemporaneity. To pics include ideology and social determination; knowledge and power; histor y, memory, and trauma; postcolonial/decolonial critique; neoliberal globali zation; biopolitics; risk and precarity.

classes.title: DIGITAL THEORY
classes.description: Histories and theories of digital media and their users, from early compute rs and networks to video games and selfies. Approaches include comparative media analysis, cultural studies, science and technology studies, software/ platform studies, and environmental media critique.

classes.title: INTERNSHIP
classes.description: An opportunity for training, career sampling, and contacts in   the film or television industry. Required are approximately   100 hours of work a quarter, a final five-page report, and a   supervisor's letter of verification.

classes.title: SENIOR HONORS SEM
classes.description: A one-quarter directed study, to be conducted as outlined in   the description of the Senior Honors Program. Honors   candidates will write a senior thesis on a topic approved by   film studies faculty.

classes.title: INDEPENDENT STUDIES
classes.description: Selected research under the direction of a faculty member.
